  "prompt": "Why do people with white skin get burnt easily?",
  "response": "People with lighter skin tones tend to burn more easily due to lower levels of melanin, the pigment responsible for giving skin its color and providing some protection against the harmful effects of ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun. Melanin absorbs and dissipates UV radiation, thereby reducing the likelihood of skin damage. Individuals with darker skin have more melanin, which offers greater protection and makes them less susceptible to sunburn.\n\nWhen people with lighter skin are exposed to UV radiation, the lower melanin levels mean less protection, leading to quicker and more severe sunburns. It's important for everyone, regardless of skin tone, to take precautions such as using sunscreen, wearing protective clothing, and avoiding excessive sun exposure to minimize the risk of skin damage and related health issues, including skin cancer.",
